Amsterdam [12][13] (Dutch: [ˌɑmstərˈdɑm] ( listen) ; lit. ' [Dam](/Dam) in the [Amstel](/Amstel)' ) [14] is the [capital](/Capital_of_the_Netherlands) [a] and [largest city](/Municipalities_of_the_Netherlands) of the [Kingdom of the Netherlands](/Kingdom_of_the_Netherlands). It has a population of 933,680 in June 2024 [15] within the city proper, 1,457,018 in the [urban area](/City_Region_of_Amsterdam) [15] and 2,480,394 in the [metropolitan area](/Metropolitan_Region_Amsterdam). [16] Located in the [Dutch province](/Provinces_of_the_Netherlands) of [North Holland](/North_Holland), [17][18] Amsterdam is colloquially referred to as the "[Venice of the North](/Venice_of_the_North)", for its [large number of canals](/Canals_of_Amsterdam), now a [UNESCO World Heritage Site](/World_Heritage_Site). [19]

Amsterdam was founded at the mouth of the [Amstel](/Amstel) River, which was dammed to control flooding. [20] Originally a small fishing village in the 12th century, Amsterdam became a major world port during the [Dutch Golden Age](/Dutch_Golden_Age) of the 17th century, when the Netherlands was an economic powerhouse. Amsterdam was the leading centre for finance and trade, as well as a hub of secular art production. [21] In the 19th and 20th centuries, the city expanded and new neighborhoods and suburbs were built. The city has a long tradition of openness, liberalism, and tolerance. [22] [Cycling](/Cycling_in_the_Netherlands) is key to the city's modern character, and there are numerous [biking paths and lanes](/Cycling_infrastructure) spread throughout. [23][24]

[Amsterdam's main attractions](/List_of_tourist_attractions_in_Amsterdam) include its [historic canals](/Canals_of_Amsterdam); the [Rijksmuseum](/Rijksmuseum), the state museum with Dutch Golden Age art; the [Van Gogh Museum](/Van_Gogh_Museum); the [Dam Square](/Dam_Square), where the [Royal Palace of Amsterdam](/Royal_Palace_of_Amsterdam) and former city hall are located; the [Amsterdam Museum](/Amsterdam_Museum); [Stedelijk Museum](/Stedelijk_Museum_Amsterdam), with modern art; the [Concertgebouw](/Concertgebouw,_Amsterdam) concert hall; the [Anne Frank House](/Anne_Frank_House); the [Scheepvaartmuseum](/Het_Scheepvaartmuseum), the [Natura Artis Magistra](/Natura_Artis_Magistra); [Hortus Botanicus](/Hortus_Botanicus_Amsterdam), [NEMO](/NEMO_(museum)), the [red-light district](/Red-light_district) and [cannabis coffee shops](/Coffeeshop_(Netherlands)). The city is known for its nightlife and festival activity, with several nightclubs among the world's most famous. Its artistic heritage, canals, and narrow canal houses with gabled [façades](/Facade), well-preserved legacies of the city's 17th-century Golden Age, have attracted millions of visitors annually.

The [Amsterdam Stock Exchange](/Amsterdam_Stock_Exchange), founded in 1602, is considered the oldest "modern" securities market [stock exchange](/Stock_exchange) in the world. As the commercial capital of the Netherlands and one of the top [financial centres](/Financial_centre) in Europe, Amsterdam is considered an [alpha-world city](/Alpha-world_city). The city is the cultural capital of the Netherlands. [25] Many large Dutch institutions have their headquarters in the city. [26] Many of the world's largest companies are based in Amsterdam or have established their European headquarters there, such as technology companies [Uber](/Uber), [Netflix](/Netflix), and [Tesla](/Tesla,_Inc.). [27] Although Amsterdam is the official [capital of the Netherlands](/Capital_of_the_Netherlands), it is not the [seat of government](/Seat_of_government). The main governmental institutions, and foreign embassies, are located in [The Hague](/The_Hague).

In 2022, Amsterdam was ranked the ninth-best city to live in by the [Economist Intelligence Unit](/Economist_Intelligence_Unit) [28] and 12th on quality of living for environment and infrastructure by Mercer. [29] The city was ranked 4th place globally as a top tech hub in 2019. [30] The [Port of Amsterdam](/Port_of_Amsterdam) is the fifth largest in Europe. [31] The [KLM](/KLM) hub and Amsterdam's main airport, [Schiphol](/Amsterdam_Airport_Schiphol), is the [busiest airport in the Netherlands](/List_of_the_busiest_airports_in_the_Netherlands), [third in Europe](/List_of_the_busiest_airports_in_Europe). The Dutch capital is one of the most multicultural cities in the world, with about 180 nationalities represented. [32] Immigration and ethnic segregation in Amsterdam is a current issue. [33]

Amsterdam's notable residents throughout [its history](/History_of_Amsterdam) include painters [Rembrandt](/Rembrandt) and [Vincent van Gogh](/Vincent_van_Gogh), 17th-century philosophers [Baruch Spinoza](/Baruch_Spinoza), [John Locke](/John_Locke), [René Descartes](/Ren%C3%A9_Descartes), and [the Holocaust](/The_Holocaust) victim and diarist [Anne Frank](/Anne_Frank).

### History

• Main article: [History of Amsterdam](/History_of_Amsterdam)
• For a chronological guide, see [Timeline of Amsterdam](/Timeline_of_Amsterdam).

It has been suggested that [History of Amsterdam](/History_of_Amsterdam) be [merged](/Wikipedia:Merging) into this article. ( [Discuss](/Talk:History_of_Amsterdam) ) Proposed since November 2025.

#### Prehistory

Due to its geographical location in what used to be wet [peatland](/Mire), the founding of Amsterdam is later than other [urban centres in the Low Countries](/History_of_urban_centers_in_the_Low_Countries). However, around the area of what later became Amsterdam, farmers settled as early as three millennia ago. They lived along the prehistoric [IJ](/IJ_(Amsterdam)) river and upstream of its [tributary](/Tributary) Amstel. The prehistoric IJ was a shallow and quiet stream in peatland behind [beach ridges](/Beach_ridge). This secluded area was able to grow into an important local settlement centre, especially in the late [Bronze Age](/Bronze_Age_Europe), the [Iron Age](/Iron_Age_Europe) and the [Roman Age](/Roman_Empire). [Neolithic](/Neolithic) and Roman artefacts have also been found in the prehistoric [Amstel](/Amstel) bedding under Amsterdam's [Damrak](/Damrak) and [Rokin](/Rokin), such as shards of [Bell Beaker culture](/Bell_Beaker_culture) [pottery](/Pottery) (2200–2000 BC) and a granite grinding stone (2700–2750 BC), [34][35] but the location of these artefacts around the river banks of the Amstel probably points to the presence of a modest semi-permanent or seasonal settlement. Until water issues were controlled, a permanent settlement would not have been possible, since the river mouth and the banks of the Amstel in this period in time were too wet for permanent habitation. [36][37]

#### Founding

• See also: [Other names of Amsterdam](/Names_of_European_cities_in_different_languages:_A)

The origins of Amsterdam are linked to the development of a dam on the [Amstel](/Amstel) River called [Amestelle](/Amstelland) , meaning 'watery area', from Aa(m) 'river' + stelle 'site at a shoreline', 'river bank'. [38] In this area, [land reclamation](/Land_reclamation) started as early as the late 10th century. [39] Amestelle was located along a side arm of the IJ. This sidearm took its name from the eponymous land: Amstel. Amestelle was inhabited by farmers, who lived more inland and more upstream, where the land was not as wet as at the banks of the downstream river mouth. These farmers were starting the reclamation around upstream [Ouderkerk aan de Amstel](/Ouderkerk_aan_de_Amstel), and later at the other side of the river at [Amstelveen](/Amstelveen). The [Van Amstel family](/Van_Amstel_family), known in documents by this name since 1019, [38] held the stewardship in this northwestern nook of the ecclesiastical district of the [bishop of Utrecht](/Prince-Bishopric_of_Utrecht). The family later served also under the [count of Holland](/County_of_Holland).

A major turning point in the development of the Amstel River mouth was the [All Saint's Flood of 1170](/All_Saints%27_Flood_(1170)). In an extremely short time, the shallow river IJ turned into a wide estuary, which from then on offered the Amstel an open connection to the [Zuiderzee](/Zuiderzee), [IJssel](/IJssel), and waterways further afield. This made the water flow of the Amstel more active, so excess water could be drained better. With drier banks, the downstream Amstel mouth became attractive for permanent habitation. Moreover, the river had grown from an insignificant peat stream into a junction of international waterways. [40] A settlement was built here immediately after the landscape change of 1170. Right from the start of its foundation, it focused on traffic, production, and trade; not on farming, as opposed to how communities had lived further upstream for the past 200 years and northward for thousands of years. [41] The construction of a dam at the mouth of the Amstel, eponymously named [Dam](/Dam_Square), is historically estimated to have occurred between 1264 and 1275. The settlement first appeared in a document from 1275, concerning a [road toll](/Road_toll_(historical)) granted by the [count of Holland Floris V](/Floris_V,_Count_of_Holland) to the residents apud Amestelledamme 'at the dam in the Amstel' or 'at the dam of Amstelland'. [42][14] This allowed the inhabitants of the village to travel freely through the [County of Holland](/County_of_Holland), paying no tolls at bridges, locks and dams. [43] This was a move in a years-long struggle for power in the area between the count of Holland and the Amstel family who governed the area on behalf of the bishop of Utrecht. [44] By 1327, the name had developed into Aemsterdam . [45][46]

• See also: [van Dam](/Van_Dam)

#### Middle Ages

The [Oude Kerk](/Oude_Kerk,_Amsterdam) was consecrated in 1306 AD.
The bishop of Utrecht granted Amsterdam zone [rights](/City_rights_in_the_Low_Countries) in either 1300 or 1306. [47] The Mirakel van Amsterdam [nl] in 1345 rendered the city an important place of [pilgrimage](/Pilgrimage). During the heyday of the [Stille Omgang](/Stille_Omgang) , which became the expression of the pilgrimage after the [Protestant Reformation](/Protestant_Reformation), [48][49] up to 90,000 pilgrims came to Amsterdam.

From the 14th century on, Amsterdam flourished, largely from trade with the [Hanseatic League](/Hanseatic_League). From the 15th century on the city established an independent [trade route with the Baltic Sea](/Baltic_maritime_trade_(c._1400%E2%80%931800)) in grain and timber, cutting out the Hanseatic League as middlemen. The city became the staple market of Europe for [bulk cargo](/Bulk_cargo). This was made possible due to innovations in the [herring fishery](/Herring), from which Amsterdam reaped great wealth. [13] Herring had demand in markets all around Europe. Inventions of on-board [gibbing](/Gibbing) and the [haringbuis](/Herring_buss) in 1415, made longer voyages feasible and hence enabled Dutch fishermen to follow the herring [shoals](/Shoaling_and_schooling) far from the coasts, giving them a monopoly in the industry.

The herring industry relied on international trade cooperation and large initial investments in ships. This required many highly skilled and unskilled workers to cooperate, as well as the import of the necessary raw materials to turn an unfinished product into a marketable one. This required merchants to then sell it throughout the continent and bookkeepers and accountants to divide the profit. In short, the herring industry was setting up the foundations for what would later become the transcontinental trade system and the [Dutch Golden Age](/Dutch_Golden_Age), with Amsterdam at its centre, [15] hence the saying "Amsterdam is built on Herringbones". [20]

#### Conflict with Spain

Amsterdam citizens celebrating the [Peace of Münster](/Peace_of_M%C3%BCnster), 30 January 1648. Painting by [Bartholomeus van der Helst](/Bartholomeus_van_der_Helst)

The Low Countries were part of the Habsburg inheritance and came under the Spanish monarchy in the early sixteenth century. The Dutch rebelled against [Philip II of Spain](/Philip_II_of_Spain), who led a defense of Catholicism during the Protestant Reformation. The main reasons for the uprising were the imposition of new taxes, the tenth penny, and the [religious persecution](/Religious_persecution) of Protestants by the newly introduced [Inquisition](/Inquisition_of_the_Netherlands). The revolt escalated into the [Eighty Years' War](/Eighty_Years%27_War), which ultimately led to Dutch independence. [50] Strongly pushed by [Dutch Revolt](/Dutch_Revolt) leader [William the Silent](/William_the_Silent), the [Dutch Republic](/Dutch_Republic) became known for its relative [religious](/History_of_religion_in_the_Netherlands) tolerance. [Jews](/History_of_the_Jews_in_the_Netherlands) from the [Iberian Peninsula](/Iberian_Peninsula), Protestant [Huguenot](/Huguenot) from France, prosperous merchants, and printers from [Flanders](/Flanders), and economic and religious refugees from the Spanish-controlled parts of the [Low Countries](/Low_Countries) found safety in Amsterdam. The influx of Flemish printers and the city's intellectual tolerance made Amsterdam a centre for the European [free press](/Freedom_of_the_press). [51]

#### Centre of the Dutch Golden Age

Courtyard of the [Amsterdam Stock Exchange](/Amsterdam_Stock_Exchange) by [Emanuel de Witte](/Emanuel_de_Witte), 1653. The [Amsterdam Stock Exchange](/Amsterdam_Stock_Exchange) was the first [stock exchange](/Stock_exchange) to introduce continuous trade in the early 17th century. [52]

During the 17th century, Amsterdam experienced what is considered its [Golden Age](/Dutch_Golden_Age), during which it became the wealthiest city in the Western world. [53] Ships sailed from Amsterdam to the [Baltic Sea](/Baltic_Sea), the Caribbean, North America, and Africa, as well as present-day [Indonesia](/Indonesia), India, [Sri Lanka](/Sri_Lanka), and [Brazil](/Brazil), forming the basis of a worldwide trading network. Amsterdam's merchants had the largest share in both the [Dutch East India Company](/Dutch_East_India_Company) (VOC) and the [Dutch West India Company](/Dutch_West_India_Company). These companies acquired overseas possessions that later became [Dutch colonies](/Dutch_Empire).

Amsterdam was Europe's most important hub for the shipment of goods and was the leading [financial centre](/Financial_centre) of the Western world. [54] In 1602, the Amsterdam office of the Dutch East India Company became the world's first [stock exchange](/Stock_exchange) by trading in its own shares. [55] The [Bank of Amsterdam](/Bank_of_Amsterdam) started operations in 1609, acting as a full-service bank for Dutch merchant bankers and as a reserve bank.

From the 17th century onwards, Amsterdam also became involved in the [Atlantic slave trade](/Atlantic_slave_trade). The city was a major destination port for Dutch [slave ships](/Slave_ship) participating in the [triangular trade](/Triangular_trade), which lasted until the [United Netherlands](/Sovereign_Principality_of_the_United_Netherlands) abolished the Netherlands' involvement in the trade in 1814 at the request of the [British government](/Government_of_the_United_Kingdom).

#### Decline and modernization

Amsterdam's prosperity declined during the 18th and early 19th centuries. The [wars](/Anglo-Dutch_Wars) of the [Dutch Republic](/Dutch_Republic) with [England](/Kingdom_of_England) (latterly, [Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain)) and France took their toll on the city. During the [French Revolutionary Wars](/French_Revolutionary_Wars) and the [Napoleonic Wars](/Napoleonic_Wars), Amsterdam's significance reached its lowest point, with Holland being absorbed into the [French Empire](/First_French_Empire). However, the later establishment of the [United Kingdom of the Netherlands](/United_Kingdom_of_the_Netherlands) in 1815 marked a turning point.

View of Vijzelstraat looking towards the [Muntplein](/Muntplein,_Amsterdam), 1891

The end of the 19th century is sometimes called Amsterdam's second Golden Age. [56] New museums, a railway station, and the [Concertgebouw](/Concertgebouw,_Amsterdam) were built; At the same time, the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution) reached the city. The [Amsterdam–Rhine Canal](/Amsterdam%E2%80%93Rhine_Canal) was dug to give Amsterdam a direct connection to the [Rhine](/Rhine), and the [North Sea Canal](/North_Sea_Canal) was dug to give the port a shorter connection to the [North Sea](/North_Sea). Both projects dramatically improved commerce with the rest of Europe and the world. In 1906, [Joseph Conrad](/Joseph_Conrad) gave a brief description of Amsterdam as seen from the seaside, in The Mirror of the Sea .

#### 20th century – present

